Analysis Plan 
Statistical models 
For the purposes of SCORE, to test H* and attempt to replicate the H* statistical evidence (if 
relevant), we will run regression analysis with random intercepts for participant and group to 
account for the nesting of 4 threshold game contributions (each with a different bonus 
variance) within individuals, who are in turn nested within 4-person groups.  
 
The regression will take the following form: 
 
Contribution = b0 + b1*losses 
 
The regressor ‘losses’ is a dummy variable representing whether or not the bonus variance has 
the possibility of losses or not (1 if medium or high variance, otherwise 0).  

 
Support for H* will be indicated if b1<0. 
 
No files selected 
Transformations 
No data 
Inference criteria 
Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is a statistically significant 
effect (alpha = .05, two tailed) in the same pattern as the original study on the focal statistical 
evidence (H*). For this test of the generalisability of McCarter et al. (2010), this criteria is met by 
a significant negative effect (alpha=.05, two tailed) of the possibility of losses on people’s 
contributions to the public good. 
Data exclusion 
Participants who fail to respond to any of the contribution decisions will be excluded from the 
study. Because participants will not be told the outcome of each game until they have 
completed all 4, it will not be necessary to exclude the rest of their group. To compute payoffs 
for members of groups where there are non-responses, we will replace the non-response with 
the minimum contribution required by each group member to reach the threshold (75 points) 
and calculate bonuses on that basis. 
Missing data 
Participants with any missing data on the DV will be excluded.  
 
Participants with missing data on the role of different strategies or demographic variables will 
not be excluded; levels of missing data will merely be reported.  
 
Exploratory analysis 
As an exploratory analysis, we will run regressions with random intercepts for participant and 
group to compare participants’ agreement that (a) loss aversion and (b) fear of 
non-contributions by others was an important strategic consideration in their contributions as a 
function of the possibility of losses. 
Other 
Other 
In an attempt to test the generalisability of McCarter et al. (2010)’s finding that loss prospects 
reduce contributions to the threshold public good, we introduced the following changes to the 
paradigm.  
 
1.​
We introduced a free-form discussion at the beginning of each round (but before 
informing participants about the bonus variance) to see whether this conditions the impact of 

the possibility of losses on contributions. Free-form discussion has been found to increase 
levels of cooperation in a wide range of settings. It is also likely to address the key reason that 
the authors postulate for reduced contributions in the face of losses: a belief that others are 
less likely to contribute.   
2.​
We dropped one of the original IVs: threshold level. In the original paper, the authors 
report that the threshold level (low, medium or high) did not condition the impact of the 
possibility of losses on contributions. We selected the medium threshold level (300 points) as 
this meant that two of the variance levels do have the possibility of losses and two of them do 
not.  
3.​
We require participants to endorse strategies on Likert scales, rather than by selecting 
the single most important strategy, as this will allow a more precise estimate of the difference 
in the importance of these strategies as a function of the possibility of losses. 
 

